@page "/tipping-point"

<PageTitle>The Tipping Point — Eq (14), (14a)</PageTitle>

<h1>The Tipping Point — Eq (14), (14a)</h1>

<blockquote>
    The tipping point is the fulcrum of the entire framework. Below F*, force decays faster than it recovers; above it, a virtuous cycle of engagement and growth takes hold. Every parameter in the model either raises or lowers this threshold.
</blockquote>

@* 1. Moving Threshold — NumberLine *@
<ChartCard Title="Moving Threshold — F* on the Number Line">
    <ChildContent>
        <NumberLine Width="600" Height="100"
                    Min="0" Max="@NumberLineMax"
                    Threshold="@FStarValue"
                    Points="@PopulationPoints" />
    </ChildContent>
    <TheoryContent>
        <h4>Equation</h4>
        <KatexBlock Latex="F^* = \frac{\beta \cdot R + \sigma \cdot M_{\text{absorbed}}}{\gamma \cdot E} \qquad (14)" />
        <h4>In Plain Language</h4>
        <p>There is a threshold level of force. Above it, the LLM accelerates your growth — you're strong enough to use it as a sparring partner, and learning compounds. Below it, the LLM accelerates your decline — you default to passive reliance, and atrophy compounds. As the F→M transfer succeeds, M_absorbed grows, which raises F*, which means more engineers fall below the threshold — not because they got weaker, but because successful transfer moved the threshold upward.</p>
        <h4>The Mirror</h4>
        <p>Above F*, the mirror functions like a dancer's studio mirror — a feedback instrument for form-correction. Below F*, it functions like Narcissus's pool — flattering, self-confirming, eventually fatal to growth. The same object. Entirely different function. Determined entirely by what stands in front of it.</p>
        <h4>Connections</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Force dynamics Eq (11)</li>
            <li>Hysteresis Eq (14a)</li>
            <li>Transfer paradox Eq (30)</li>
        </ul>
    </TheoryContent>
</ChartCard>

@* 2. Parameter Decomposition — TornadoDiagram *@
<ChartCard Title="Parameter Decomposition — Tornado Diagram">
    <ChildContent>
        <TornadoDiagram Width="600" Height="300" Factors="@TornadoFactors" />
    </ChildContent>
    <TheoryContent>
        <h4>Equation</h4>
        <KatexBlock Latex="F^* = \frac{\beta \cdot R + \sigma \cdot M_{\text{absorbed}}}{\gamma \cdot E} \qquad (14)" />
        <h4>In Plain Language</h4>
        <p>F* is sensitive to four parameters. Increasing passive reliance (β·R) or model absorption (σ·M_absorbed) raises the threshold, putting more people at risk. Increasing deliberate engagement (γ·E) lowers it, creating safety margin. The tornado diagram reveals which levers have the most impact on who falls below the tipping point.</p>
        <h4>Connections</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Organizational de-investment Eq (11)</li>
            <li>Transfer rate Eq (26)</li>
            <li>Diverging trajectories Eq (15a-b)</li>
        </ul>
    </TheoryContent>
</ChartCard>

@* 3. Phase Portrait — dF/dt vs F *@
<ChartCard Title="Phase Portrait — dF/dt vs F">
    <ChildContent>
        <PhasePortrait Width="600" Height="400"
                       XLabel="F (Force)" YLabel="dF/dt"
                       Curve="@PhaseCurve"
                       ZeroCrossing="@FStarValue" />
    </ChildContent>
    <TheoryContent>
        <h4>Equation</h4>
        <KatexBlock Latex="\frac{dF}{dt} = \alpha \cdot S + \gamma \cdot E \cdot F - \beta \cdot R - \sigma \cdot M_{\text{absorbed}} \qquad (11)" />
        <h4>In Plain Language</h4>
        <p>The phase portrait shows two stable equilibria. Where dF/dt crosses zero from positive to negative is the tipping point F*. To the right, force grows (the γEF compounding engine dominates). To the left, force decays (the βR drag dominates). The shape of the curve reveals the strength of each basin of attraction.</p>
        <h4>Connections</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Tipping point Eq (14)</li>
            <li>Diverging trajectories Eq (15a-b)</li>
            <li>Terminal dynamics</li>
        </ul>
    </TheoryContent>
</ChartCard>

@* 4. Hysteresis Funnel — Decay vs Recovery *@
<ChartCard Title="Hysteresis Funnel — Decay vs Recovery at F*">
    <ChildContent>
        <NumberLine Width="600" Height="100"
                    Min="@HysteresisMin" Max="@HysteresisMax"
                    Threshold="0"
                    Points="@HysteresisPoints" />
        <p class="hysteresis-caption">
            @if (HysteresisPresent)
            {
                <strong class="hysteresis-alert">Hysteresis detected:</strong> @(" decay rate exceeds recovery rate")
            }
            else
            {
                <span>No hysteresis: recovery rate meets or exceeds decay rate</span>
            }
        </p>
    </ChildContent>
    <TheoryContent>
        <h4>Equation</h4>
        <KatexBlock Latex="\left|\frac{dF}{dt}\right|_{\text{decay}} > \left|\frac{dF}{dt}\right|_{\text{recovery}} \quad \text{for the same distance from } F^* \qquad (14a)" />
        <h4>In Plain Language</h4>
        <p>Falling below the tipping point isn't just entering a decay trajectory. It's entering a trajectory that's harder to escape than it was to enter. The first time you struggle through a debugging session, there's first-contact novelty that aids encoding. Re-learning after atrophy lacks that novelty, feels more tedious, and competes against the knowledge that the LLM shortcut exists. F* is a cliff, not a hill.</p>
        <h4>Connections</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Tipping point Eq (14)</li>
            <li>Force dynamics Eq (11)</li>
            <li>Cohort discontinuity Eq (32)</li>
        </ul>
    </TheoryContent>
</ChartCard>

